[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:zap-logging-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:zap-logging-go/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:zap-logging-go/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
